    surahBasicDetail:
      '  <body >      This early Makkan surat was revealed before the first wave of migration to Abyssinia, in the fifth year of the Prophet&rsquo;s  ‎‎[PBUH]  mission. The surat is lyrical, most verses ending with a long vowel &ldquo;aa&rdquo;&ndash; a generous peppering of (Yaa) and (Daa) beautifies a familiar subject. This is complemented with the repetition of the divine name (al-Rahman) (the Most Kind) sixteen times.It opens with the solemn prayer of Prophet Zakariyya, عليه السلام for a successor. He was old, childless, and worried about who would be his heir. This prayer reflects his deep faith and reliance on Allah: &ldquo;My prayer has never gone unanswered by My Lord&rdquo; (4). Allah blessed him with Yahya عليه السلام, &ldquo;The soft-hearted, pure and pious&rdquo; (13). The story of the miraculous conception and birth of Isa عليه السلام emphasises the Power, Majesty and Independent nature of the Divine, who is beyond the law of cause and effect. The first words \n(Isa) عليه السلام said: &ldquo;I am a servant of Allah; He has given me the Book and made me a prophet, and made me blessed wherever I go&rdquo; (31). The Quran rejects the Christian belief of Trinity, and states how objectionable and unacceptable this is to Allah: &ldquo;What a monstrous thing you have said! Even the skies would crack, the Earth would rip apart and the mountains crumble&rdquo; (89&ndash;91). This outrageous claim shows the extent of Allah&rsquo;s anger, a powerful condemnation of idolatry.A highly-charged conversation then follows between a nephew and an uncle: Ibrahim عليه السلام very gently tries to persuade and win over Azar, his uncle, from idolatry. The courtesy and logic he employs are persuasive enough to prompt even a stone heart to move. However, idolatry makes one deaf, locks the mind and seals the heart. Ibrahim عليه السلام sets a wonderful example for preachers and obedient sons on how to differ politely. There are four stories mentioned here: Zakariyya عليه السلام and Yahya عليه السلام, Maryam عليه السلام and Isa عليه السلام, Ibrahim عليه السلام and Azar, Musa عليه السلام and Harun عليه السلام. They reflect a father and son relationship, a mother and son relationship, and two brotherly relationships. The relationships between prophets and their communities also reveal the great importance of human relationships.Faith forms an important element of relationships. The Quran condemns those generations who were the children of prophets yet: &ldquo;After them came generations who neglected the prayer and followed their lusts. Soon they will face the consequences of their evil&rdquo; (59). Salah is a powerful expression of a person&rsquo;s relationship with Allah, the Lord. Neglecting it demonstrates a lack of commitment to the relationship. Yet Allah&rsquo;s love for believers is remarkable: &ldquo;The Kind Lord will make for them love (in people&rsquo;s hearts&rdquo); (96). This could also be taken to mean: &ldquo;The Kind Lord loves them dearly.&rdquo;  </body>',
