      '  <body >     \t      This is an early Makkan surat, its central theme is how Allah guides humanity through messengers, exemplified by featuring the life story of Musa عليه السلام. The story begins when Musa عليه السلام is returning from Madyan to Egypt. He is appointed as a messenger and given miracles. The surat flips back to the time of his birth, recalling how as a baby he was rescued from Pharaoh’s murderous plan: “I wrapped you up in My Divine Love so that you may grow up under My Eyes” (39). How loving is Allah! Musa عليه السلام heads straight for Pharaoh’s court. A heated conversation follows and the Pharaoh gets angry, but Musa boldly – yet gently – continues to invite him to Allah. Despite witnessing the two miracles of Musa عليه السلام, the Pharaoh remains stubbornly unwilling to listen to him. He mistakenly believes Musa عليه السلام is a magician so challenges him to duel his magicians.              A vivid description of the duel offers insights into the working of magic, and why magic failed. These expert magicians realised that Musa عليه السلام was not a magician, so they accepted his victory and his prophethood. The Pharaoh was enraged and had them martyred.              Even after this defeat and witnessing nine miracles, the Pharaoh refused to accept Musa عليه السلام. Finally, Musa عليه السلام led the Israelites out of Egypt. The Pharaoh chased them, but was drowned. Once in the Sinai Peninsula, the Israelites enjoyed freedom and were blessed with the Heavenly gifts of quail and Manna. However, when Musa عليه السلام left them for a short while – he visited Mount Sinai to meet Allah – the Israelites made an idol to worship. Musa عليه السلام was angry with his brother Harun for not stopping them. Samiri the Goldsmith, the mastermind of this ordeal, forged a golden calf and Musa عليه السلام cursed him for his blasphemy and evil action.              As a commentary on the story of Musa عليه السلام, the Quran tells the Makkans to learn a lesson: the Quran is a reminder, and warns of the dire consequences of rejecting the Prophet  ‎‎[PBUH] .              The surat opened by telling the beloved Prophet Mustafa  ‎‎[PBUH]  not to be stressed by sarcasm and scornful attitude of Makkans, at the end he’s told: be patient, be calm, and seek help through constant prayer.      </body>',
